This paper proposes a neural architecture for natural language inference, which falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP). Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also uses attention mechanisms, which are commonly used in machine learning and artificial intelligence (AI), making cs.AI the second likely sub-category. The paper also achieves state-of-the-art results, which is a common goal in machine learning and falls under the category of machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also mentions the use of parallelization, which is a common technique in neural networks and falls under the category of neural networks (cs.NE). Finally, the paper uses the Stanford Natural Language Inference (SNLI) dataset, which is a commonly used dataset in NLP and computer vision (cs.CV).
